defaultEducation for self management
default&#xa0;
default2.7
default 
defaultIt is estimated that around 95% of diabetes care is self management. NICE guidelines, backed by strong international evidence
default, recommend that structured education is made available to all people with diabetes to help them understand and manage their diabetes. 
default&#xa0;
default2.8 But too few people are offered it and not enough attend courses:
default&#xa0;
defaultThe interaction between mental health conditions and long-term physical health conditionsdefault&#xa0;default2.9
default 
defaultThere is a greater prevalence of psychological conditions such as depression, anxiety and eating disorders among people with diabetes than the general population
default. Poor emotional wellbeing is associated with sub optimal blood glucose control, which in turn can lead to the development of complications. For example, depression is twice as common in people with diabetes and can have an affect on an individual’s ability to control their diet or manage their medication
default. 
default2.10
default 
defaultDespite this, and the fact that treatment of psychological conditions has been shown to improve psychological wellbeing and other health related
default outcomes
default, 85%
default of people with diabetes have no access to psychological care and 
defaultsupport
default.
default 
defaultAccess to emotional and psychological care 
defaultshould 
defaultbecome a routin
defaulte part of diabetes management, 
defaultreduc
defaulting
default the ‘costs’ of untreated psychological conditions.
