defaultManaging contributory factors
default&#xa0;
defaultObesity as a contributory factor to Type 2 diabetes default&#xa0;
default4.1
default 
defaultObesity 
defaultaccounts for 80-85%
default of the overall risk of developing Type 2 diabetes
default. As almost two in every three people in the UK are overweight or obese
default, the main strategy for reducing the rising prevalence of Type 2 diabetes should be to tackle the rise in obesity. 
defaultF
defaultull implementation of the NHS Health Check programme 
defaultwould lead to better early diagnosis and prevention of diabetes. 
defaultOther 
defaultpriorities are: 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe implications of an ageing population for the prevalence of diabetes, and the extent to which services have the capacity to meet future demandsdefault&#xa0;default4.2
default 
defaultOlder people are more likely to have diabetes. 
defaultIn England the prevalence of diabetes across all ages is 
defaultcurrently 
default5.5
default%
default. This increases with age to 14
default%
default prevalence in over 65s
default. It is likely therefore, that the ageing population will contribute significantly to the increasing prevalence of diabetes
default and co-morbidities
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default 
defaultCurrent services do not have the capacity to meet predicted future demand. 
defaultThis is largely 
defaultbecause
default diabetes in older people requires careful management due to the complex interaction between the process of ageing, the increased prevalence of co-morbidities, widespread vascular disease and functional loss.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.4
default 
defaultIt is therefore essential that prevention, education, better care and the i
defaultmplementation 
defaultof integrated pathways of care are prioritised to address this. 
